{"type":"message","id":"958e4160","parentId":"dd0d67f4","timestamp":"2026-03-24T21:05:43.411Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"LinkedIn admin page is open and logged in. I can see the Nava page with \"No posts published yet.\" Let me check for any existing LI002 draft before writing fresh.\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"ollama_call_ce09bb61-e94a-497d-8410-8439b7cc7a67","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"ls -la /home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace/rag/drafts/ | grep -i \"li\\|linkedin\\|002\\|post\""}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"ollama_call_3e691ef2-a885-4aad-a5b9-15ecc4b5eb97","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cat /home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace/rag/drafts/posted_draft_001.md"}}],"stopReason":"toolUse","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":34111,"output":419,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":34530,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1774386343411}}
{"type":"message","id":"61cbec51","parentId":"958e4160","timestamp":"2026-03-24T21:05:43.431Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"ollama_call_ce09bb61-e94a-497d-8410-8439b7cc7a67","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"-rw-rw-r--  1 tiny4lurv tiny4lurv     1884 Mar 24 23:03 li002_final.md\n-rw-rw-r--  1 tiny4lurv tiny4lurv     2180 Mar 20 00:44 posted_draft_001.md"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":12,"aggregated":"-rw-rw-r--  1 tiny4lurv tiny4lurv     1884 Mar 24 23:03 li002_final.md\n-rw-rw-r--  1 tiny4lurv tiny4lurv     2180 Mar 20 00:44 posted_draft_001.md","cwd":"/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774386343430}}
{"type":"message","id":"b36acbbb","parentId":"61cbec51","timestamp":"2026-03-24T21:05:43.433Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"ollama_call_3e691ef2-a885-4aad-a5b9-15ecc4b5eb97","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"---\nplatform: LinkedIn\nauthor: Nava Healthcare Recruitment\nurl: https://www.linkedin.com/feed/update/urn:li:activity:7440527552143597568\ndate: 2026-03-19\nstatus: posted\ntype: post-first\nimage: none (CTA links to article)\n\n𝗪𝗵𝗮𝘁 𝗶𝗳 𝘆𝗼𝘂𝗿 𝗿𝗲𝗰𝗿𝘂𝗶𝘁𝗺𝗲𝗻𝘁 𝗳𝗲𝗲 𝘄𝗮𝘀 𝘀𝗽𝗿𝗲𝗮𝗱 𝗼𝘃𝗲𝗿 𝟭𝟮 𝘄𝗲𝗲𝗸𝘀? For every week your new hire stays, your agency gets 8–10% more of the full fee. They hit 100% at week 12.\n\nSounds 𝘣𝘦𝘵𝘵𝘦𝘳, right?\n\nYour agency would actually care about compatibility. They'd follow up and worry if someone might quit at week 3 because that's money left on the table.\n\nBut tricks are for kids, and here's why this dream will never work in practice.\n\n𝗔𝗱𝗺𝗻𝗶𝘀𝘁𝗿𝗮𝘁𝗶𝘃𝗲𝗹𝘆: Spreading payments over 12 weeks is a nightmare for your HR department. Tracking, invoicing, and reconciliation; it multiplies the workload.\n\n𝗔𝗴𝗲𝗻𝗰𝗶𝗲𝘀 𝗵𝗮𝘃𝗲 𝗮 𝗳𝗮𝗶𝗿 𝗮𝗿𝗴𝘂𝗺𝗲𝗻𝘁: They've done the sourcing, vetting, presenting, and placing. They've found your candidate and got them through the door. Why wait 3 months to get paid in full?\n\nRegardless, this model is objectively better for healthcare facilities, yet it's impractical. No agency would jeopardize its revenue to make it even more unpredictable.\n\nAt Nava, we don't stretch the fee over 12 weeks. We put our money where our mouth is. 𝗭𝗲𝗿𝗼 𝘂𝗽𝗳𝗿𝗼𝗻𝘁 𝗰𝗼𝘀𝘁𝘀. We get paid only when your hire proves themselves.\n\nWe get it. As former healthcare executives, we were frustrated each time an early resignation cost us time and money. We built Nava around a different philosophy — not how we charge, but how we align.\n\n𝘛𝘩𝘢𝘵'𝘴 𝘫𝘶𝘴𝘵 𝘥𝘰𝘪𝘯𝘨 𝘁𝘩𝘪𝘯𝘨𝘴 𝗱𝗶𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗿𝗲𝗻𝘁𝗹𝘆.\n\nWe wrote about what actually to look for in a medical recruiting agency and why we built Nava around a different philosophy: 👉 https://navahc.com/how-to-find-the-best-medical-recruiting-agencies/\n---"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":8,"aggregated":"---\nplatform: LinkedIn\nauthor: Nava Healthcare Recruitment\nurl: https://www.linkedin.com/feed/update/urn:li:activity:7440527552143597568\ndate: 2026-03-19\nstatus: posted\ntype: post-first\nimage: none (CTA links to article)\n\n𝗪𝗵𝗮𝘁 𝗶𝗳 𝘆𝗼𝘂𝗿 𝗿𝗲𝗰𝗿𝘂𝗶𝘁𝗺𝗲𝗻𝘁 𝗳𝗲𝗲 𝘄𝗮𝘀 𝘀𝗽𝗿𝗲𝗮𝗱 𝗼𝘃𝗲𝗿 𝟭𝟮 𝘄𝗲𝗲𝗸𝘀? For every week your new hire stays, your agency gets 8–10% more of the full fee. They hit 100% at week 12.\n\nSounds 𝘣𝘦𝘵𝘵𝘦𝘳, right?\n\nYour agency would actually care about compatibility. They'd follow up and worry if someone might quit at week 3 because that's money left on the table.\n\nBut tricks are for kids, and here's why this dream will never work in practice.\n\n𝗔𝗱𝗺𝗻𝗶𝘀𝘁𝗿𝗮𝘁𝗶𝘃𝗲𝗹𝘆: Spreading payments over 12 weeks is a nightmare for your HR department. Tracking, invoicing, and reconciliation; it multiplies the workload.\n\n𝗔𝗴𝗲𝗻𝗰𝗶𝗲𝘀 𝗵𝗮𝘃𝗲 𝗮 𝗳𝗮𝗶𝗿 𝗮𝗿𝗴𝘂𝗺𝗲𝗻𝘁: They've done the sourcing, vetting, presenting, and placing. They've found your candidate and got them through the door. Why wait 3 months to get paid in full?\n\nRegardless, this model is objectively better for healthcare facilities, yet it's impractical. No agency would jeopardize its revenue to make it even more unpredictable.\n\nAt Nava, we don't stretch the fee over 12 weeks. We put our money where our mouth is. 𝗭𝗲𝗿𝗼 𝘂𝗽𝗳𝗿𝗼𝗻𝘁 𝗰𝗼𝘀𝘁𝘀. We get paid only when your hire proves themselves.\n\nWe get it. As former healthcare executives, we were frustrated each time an early resignation cost us time and money. We built Nava around a different philosophy — not how we charge, but how we align.\n\n𝘛𝘩𝘢𝘵'𝘴 𝘫𝘶𝘴𝘵 𝘥𝘰𝘪𝘯𝘨 𝘁𝘩𝘪𝘯𝘨𝘴 𝗱𝗶𝗳𝗳𝗲𝗿𝗲𝗻𝘁𝗹𝘆.\n\nWe wrote about what actually to look for in a medical recruiting agency and why we built Nava around a different philosophy: 👉 https://navahc.com/how-to-find-the-best-medical-recruiting-agencies/\n---","cwd":"/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774386343432}}
{"type":"message","id":"904bd9df","parentId":"b36acbbb","timestamp":"2026-03-24T21:05:46.310Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"ollama_call_0029405c-19d8-4737-a71e-c6e8d7e0868d","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace/rag/drafts/li002_final.md"}}],"stopReason":"toolUse","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":34989,"output":58,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":35047,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1774386346310}}
{"type":"message","id":"c14de7bc","parentId":"904bd9df","timestamp":"2026-03-24T21:05:46.316Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"ollama_call_0029405c-19d8-4737-a71e-c6e8d7e0868d","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# LI002 — \"The 13-Week Problem in LTC\" (Final Draft — Posted Mar 24, 2026)\n\n**Hook:** Census argument — LTC patients are cognitively impaired; the 13-week travel cycle is uniquely harmful to this population, not just inconvenient\n\n**Post:**\n---\nIn long-term care, the patient at the end of the hall has been disoriented three times this year.\n\nThe same routine. A different face. A different name.\n\nIn hospitals, travel nurses fill shifts. In long-term care, they fill something more fragile: the patient's sense of safety in a world they can no longer navigate alone.\n\nLong-term care residents are older, sicker, and more cognitively impaired than any acute care population. They cannot adapt to new faces every 13 weeks. Research shows that repeated staff turnover in dementia units correlates with measurable clinical deterioration — not inconvenience, deterioration.\n\nThe 13-week cycle was built for hospitals. It was never built for memory care.\n\nThe alternative isn't a better travel agency. It's a different model entirely.\n\nInternational nurses on EB-3 green card pathways commit to three-year terms — 6,000 hours of embedded, relational care. They learn the unit. They learn the patients. They stay.\n\nFacilities running this math see the numbers clearly: replacing a single travel nurse with a permanent hire saves an average of $79,100 per year. Over a facility running 50 travel roles, that compounds into something that changes the economics of the entire building.\n\nThat's the LTC staffing model nobody is talking about.\n\nNava Healthcare Recruitment — permanent international placements for facilities that need stability, not cycles.\n---\n\n**Posted:** 2026-03-24 ~21:00 UTC\n**Platform:** Nava Healthcare Recruitment LinkedIn Page\n**Status:** ✅ LIVE\n**Post URL:** https://www.linkedin.com/feed/update/urn:li:share:7442315133936254976?actorCompanyId=67170741\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774386346315}}
